{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17476713","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17476713"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:50:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:50:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13937"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13937","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13937"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.51,0.07,0.03,0.32,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6563"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106826"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6563","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6563"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13937"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89312"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"302"},{"type":"tags","id":"1674"},{"type":"tags","id":"1710"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2706"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"9689"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12916"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13243"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38970"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39022"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44183"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106826","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106826"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA three-week-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with lethargy and poor feeding for 24 hours. He was born at term with no complications and has been well prior to the last 24 hours. All antenatal care and investigations were unremarkable. On examination, he appears mottled with a pulse rate of 170/min, blood pressure 65/35 mmHg, respiratory rate 65/min, temperature 35.2\u00b0C, and capillary refill time of four seconds. Initial investigations show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlood glucose: 2.4 mmol/L (3.3-7.8)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EVenous pH: 7.18 (7.32-7.42)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBicarbonate: 11 mmol/L (22-26)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Septic shock","Critical congenital heart disease","Non-accidental injury","Inborn error of metabolism","Midgut volvulus"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis infant presents with features highly suggestive of \u003Cstrong\u003Eseptic shock\u003C/strong\u003E, including poor perfusion (mottling, prolonged capillary refill), hypothermia, tachycardia, hypotension, hypoglycaemia and metabolic acidosis. Neonatal sepsis requires urgent recognition and treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHypoglycaemia is a common finding in neonatal sepsis due to a combination of poor feeding and increase in metabolic demand. It is important to consider metabolic causes but when combined with cardiovascular compromise, hypothermia, acute presentation and lethargy with rapid onset, this makes sepsis the more likely diagnosis in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECritical congenital heart disease\u003C/strong\u003E can present similarly, particularly when duct-dependent lesions decompensate. However, the metabolic acidosis and hypoglycaemia are more suggestive of sepsis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003Enon-accidental injury\u003C/strong\u003E must always be considered in an unwell infant, there are no specific features in the history or examination to suggest this as the primary diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Einborn error of metabolism\u003C/strong\u003E could explain the hypoglycaemia and acidosis, but the cardiovascular compromise and acute presentation at three weeks is more typical of sepsis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMidgut volvulus\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with bilious vomiting and abdominal distension, which are not described here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe combination of circulatory compromise, metabolic derangement, and acute deterioration makes septic shock the most likely diagnosis requiring immediate intervention.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The differential diagnosis for a lethargic neonate should include sepsis, cardiac conditions, abuse, metabolic disorders, and surgical emergencies (SCAMS).","A systematic approach including thorough examination and targeted investigations is essential in evaluating an unwell neonate.","Early recognition and treatment of neonatal sepsis is crucial as it can present with non-specific symptoms."],"references":["National Guideline Alliance (UK). Signs and symptoms of serious illness in babies: Postnatal care: Evidence review L1. London: National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE); 2021 Apr. (NICE Guideline, No. 194.) Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK571555/","South Thames Retrieval Service (SORT). Neonatal Collapse Guidelines. London: South Thames Retrieval Service; 2016 [cited 2024 Nov 21]. Available from: https://www.sort.nhs.uk/Media/Guidelines/Neonatalcollapse.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89312"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13937"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89312","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89312"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-23T09:07:37+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-23T13:53:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6563"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106826"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"78","links":{"self":"https